{"parentUuid":"c046ccac-a183-413b-81fe-b885c98259fd","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Ldn7cm6W1XU813vcDSbKrY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017KfeaxJKizXvvs7j5zxyiY","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"generator-verifier gap verification easier than generation LLM amplify weak generator"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5962,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"output_tokens":317,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5962},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":317,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5962,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5962,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":7790}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG24Ugrbk5R76W1AiMRN","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"5ba70cfd-353c-464f-ad2c-0b15b18f9011","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:55.740Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"472097e5-afe2-442a-983d-97319b72a93a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VczJUwhGjnXcXb7MNLPjPq","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Large Language Monkeys repeated sampling coverage scaling Brown 2024 pass@k\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2407.21787] Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\"},{\"title\":\"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford University\",\"url\":\"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/pubs/large_language_monkeys/\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - ScalingIntelligence/large_language_monkeys\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ScalingIntelligence/large_language_monkeys\"},{\"title\":\"Monkey Business: a Dataset of Large LLM Sample Collections for Math and Code Tasks | Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford University\",\"url\":\"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/blogs/monkeys/\"},{\"title\":\"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0xUEBQV54B\"},{\"title\":\"[Research Paper Summary] Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | by Himanshu Bamoria | Athina AI | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/athina-ai/large-language-monkeys-scaling-inference-compute-with-repeated-sampling-4de85a3e1384\"},{\"title\":\"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.21787\"},{\"title\":\"Test-Time Scaling Makes Overtraining Compute-Optimal\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.01411\"},{\"title\":\"More Bang for the Buck: Improving the Inference of Large Language Models at a Fixed Budget using Reset and Discard (ReD)\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.21522\"},{\"title\":\"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling - Paper Detail\",\"url\":\"https://deeplearn.org/arxiv/514186/large-language-monkeys:-scaling-inference-compute-with-repeated-sampling\"}]\n\nI found the research paper you're looking for! Here are the key findings:\n\n## Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling\n\nThe paper explores inference compute as a scaling axis using repeated sampling of candidate solutions from a model. Across multiple tasks and models, coverage—the fraction of problems that are solved by any generated sample—scales with the number of samples over four orders of magnitude.\n\nThe relationship between coverage and the number of samples is often log-linear and can be modelled with an exponentiated power law, suggesting the existence of inference-time scaling laws.\n\n### Practical Results\n\nWhen applying repeated sampling to SWE-bench Lite, the fraction of issues solved with DeepSeek-V2-Coder-Instruct increases from 15.9% with one sample to 56% with 250 samples, outperforming the single-attempt state-of-the-art of 43% which uses more capable frontier models.\n\nIn domains like coding and formal proofs, where answers can be automatically verified, these increases in coverage directly translate into improved performance.\n\n**Authors:** Bradley Brown, Jordan Juravsky, Ryan Ehrlich, Ronald Clark, Quoc V. Le, Christopher Ré, and Azalia Mirhoseini\n\n**Publication:** July 31, 2024 (arXiv:2407.21787)\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"2450e15e-45a7-407f-b673-1860a2d8408b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:01.330Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Large Language Monkeys repeated sampling coverage scaling Brown 2024 pass@k","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_018dofTtDDzp8TRWp7BZ8tVk","content":[{"title":"[2407.21787] Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787"},{"title":"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford University","url":"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/pubs/large_language_monkeys/"},{"title":"GitHub - ScalingIntelligence/large_language_monkeys","url":"https://github.com/ScalingIntelligence/large_language_monkeys"},{"title":"Monkey Business: a Dataset of Large LLM Sample Collections for Math and Code Tasks | Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford University","url":"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/blogs/monkeys/"},{"title":"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0xUEBQV54B"},{"title":"[Research Paper Summary] Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling | by Himanshu Bamoria | Athina AI | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/athina-ai/large-language-monkeys-scaling-inference-compute-with-repeated-sampling-4de85a3e1384"},{"title":"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.21787"},{"title":"Test-Time Scaling Makes Overtraining Compute-Optimal","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.01411"},{"title":"More Bang for the Buck: Improving the Inference of Large Language Models at a Fixed Budget using Reset and Discard (ReD)","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.21522"},{"title":"Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling - Paper Detail","url":"https://deeplearn.org/arxiv/514186/large-language-monkeys:-scaling-inference-compute-with-repeated-sampling"}]},"I found the research paper you're looking for! Here are the key findings:\n\n## Large Language Monkeys: Scaling Inference Compute with Repeated Sampling\n\nThe paper explores inference compute as a scaling axis using repeated sampling of candidate solutions from a model. Across multiple tasks and models, coverage—the fraction of problems that are solved by any generated sample—scales with the number of samples over four orders of magnitude.\n\nThe relationship between coverage and the number of samples is often log-linear and can be modelled with an exponentiated power law, suggesting the existence of inference-time scaling laws.\n\n### Practical Results\n\nWhen applying repeated sampling to SWE-bench Lite, the fraction of issues solved with DeepSeek-V2-Coder-Instruct increases from 15.9% with one sample to 56% with 250 samples, outperforming the single-attempt state-of-the-art of 43% which uses more capable frontier models.\n\nIn domains like coding and formal proofs, where answers can be automatically verified, these increases in coverage directly translate into improved performance.\n\n**Authors:** Bradley Brown, Jordan Juravsky, Ryan Ehrlich, Ronald Clark, Quoc V. Le, Christopher Ré, and Azalia Mirhoseini\n\n**Publication:** July 31, 2024 (arXiv:2407.21787)"],"durationSeconds":7.001142875000834,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"472097e5-afe2-442a-983d-97319b72a93a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2f587827-a2dd-48ab-9b4f-bf47776b9c7c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UDN6Dekr7qVvTbvJWqfyBU","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"scaling test-time compute optimally Snell 2024 small model outperform 14x larger\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters | by Eleventh Hour Enthusiast | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@EleventhHourEnthusiast/scaling-llm-test-time-compute-optimally-can-be-more-effective-than-scaling-model-parameters-19a0c9fb7c44\"},{\"title\":\"This Week in AI Research — Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally: Why Small Models Can Beat…\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@notsokarda/this-week-in-ai-research-scaling-llm-test-time-compute-optimally-why-small-models-can-beat-d7fd7c895065\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - adikal25/Scaling-LLM-Test-Time-Compute-Optimally-can-be-More-Effective-than-Scaling-Model-Parameters · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/adikal25/Scaling-LLM-Test-Time-Compute-Optimally-can-be-More-Effective-than-Scaling-Model-Parameters\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/382914793_Scaling_LLM_Test-Time_Compute_Optimally_can_be_More_Effective_than_Scaling_Model_Parameters\"},{\"title\":\"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters\",\"url\":\"https://whoisnnamdi.com/notes/@snellScalingLLMTestTime2024/\"},{\"title\":\"[2408.03314] Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.03314\"},{\"title\":\"How to Upscale Neural Networks with Scaling Law? A Survey and Practical Guidelines\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12051\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time   Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.06703\"},{\"title\":\"AgentTTS: Large Language Model Agent for Test-time Compute-optimal Scaling Strategy in Complex Tasks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.00890\"},{\"title\":\"Efficient Test-Time Scaling via Self-Calibration\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.00031\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found information about the Snell et al. 2024 paper on scaling test-time compute optimally.\n\n## Key Findings\n\nIn a FLOPs-matched evaluation, the research found that a smaller base model can outperform a 14x larger model using test-time compute. By allocating inference-time computation adaptively, they show that a smaller model can outperform one 14× larger at matched compute — achieving 4× higher efficiency.\n\n## The Research\n\nThe paper is authored by Charlie Snell (UC Berkeley), Jaehoon Lee, Kelvin Xu, and Aviral Kumar (Google DeepMind). The research analyzes two primary mechanisms to scale test-time computation: searching against dense, process-based verifier reward models, and updating the model's distribution over a response adaptively. The effectiveness of different approaches to scaling test-time compute critically varies depending on the difficulty of the prompt.\n\n## Practical Impact\n\nUsing this compute-optimal strategy, they can improve the efficiency of test-time compute scaling by more than 4x compared to a best-of-N baseline. Their findings challenge the industry's fixation on model size and show that smart test-time compute allocation can be more efficient — and more powerful — than traditional scaling.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"872e9381-7447-4869-b93d-e77d51f242fb","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:04.791Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"scaling test-time compute optimally Snell 2024 small model outperform 14x larger","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01KQbCNawHghsbcB9cSXS5Br","content":[{"title":"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters | by Eleventh Hour Enthusiast | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@EleventhHourEnthusiast/scaling-llm-test-time-compute-optimally-can-be-more-effective-than-scaling-model-parameters-19a0c9fb7c44"},{"title":"This Week in AI Research — Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally: Why Small Models Can Beat…","url":"https://medium.com/@notsokarda/this-week-in-ai-research-scaling-llm-test-time-compute-optimally-why-small-models-can-beat-d7fd7c895065"},{"title":"GitHub - adikal25/Scaling-LLM-Test-Time-Compute-Optimally-can-be-More-Effective-than-Scaling-Model-Parameters · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/adikal25/Scaling-LLM-Test-Time-Compute-Optimally-can-be-More-Effective-than-Scaling-Model-Parameters"},{"title":"(PDF) Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/382914793_Scaling_LLM_Test-Time_Compute_Optimally_can_be_More_Effective_than_Scaling_Model_Parameters"},{"title":"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters","url":"https://whoisnnamdi.com/notes/@snellScalingLLMTestTime2024/"},{"title":"[2408.03314] Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally can be More Effective than Scaling Model Parameters","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.03314"},{"title":"How to Upscale Neural Networks with Scaling Law? A Survey and Practical Guidelines","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12051"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time   Scaling","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.06703"},{"title":"AgentTTS: Large Language Model Agent for Test-time Compute-optimal Scaling Strategy in Complex Tasks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.00890"},{"title":"Efficient Test-Time Scaling via Self-Calibration","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.00031"}]},"Based on the search results, I found information about the Snell et al. 2024 paper on scaling test-time compute optimally.\n\n## Key Findings\n\nIn a FLOPs-matched evaluation, the research found that a smaller base model can outperform a 14x larger model using test-time compute. By allocating inference-time computation adaptively, they show that a smaller model can outperform one 14× larger at matched compute — achieving 4× higher efficiency.\n\n## The Research\n\nThe paper is authored by Charlie Snell (UC Berkeley), Jaehoon Lee, Kelvin Xu, and Aviral Kumar (Google DeepMind). The research analyzes two primary mechanisms to scale test-time computation: searching against dense, process-based verifier reward models, and updating the model's distribution over a response adaptively. The effectiveness of different approaches to scaling test-time compute critically varies depending on the difficulty of the prompt.\n\n## Practical Impact\n\nUsing this compute-optimal strategy, they can improve the efficiency of test-time compute scaling by more than 4x compared to a best-of-N baseline. Their findings challenge the industry's fixation on model size and show that smart test-time compute allocation can be more efficient — and more powerful — than traditional scaling."],"durationSeconds":9.964900708999485,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2f587827-a2dd-48ab-9b4f-bf47776b9c7c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"5ba70cfd-353c-464f-ad2c-0b15b18f9011","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017KfeaxJKizXvvs7j5zxyiY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"generator-verifier gap verification easier than generation LLM amplify weak generator\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Weaver: Closing the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers · Hazy Research\",\"url\":\"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2025-06-18-weaver\"},{\"title\":\"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1\"},{\"title\":\"Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf/2746494c2d2444d3341c92778e3a660a0f237fd2.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers - Video | MLOps Community\",\"url\":\"https://home.mlops.community/public/videos/shrinking-the-generation-verification-gap-with-weak-verifiers\"},{\"title\":\"Aggregating LLM-Based Weak Verifiers for Spatial Layout Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.05268\"},{\"title\":\"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers\",\"url\":\"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/pubs/weaver.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Variation in Verification: Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.17995\"},{\"title\":\"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.18203\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about the generator-verifier gap and how verification relates to generation in LLMs:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nBy aggregating weak, unlabeled verifier signals using weak supervision, Weaver closes the generation-verification gap without fine-tuning, significant human labeling, or architectural changes.\n\n### Verification Can Be Easier Than Generation\n\nLanguage models often already \"know\" the correct answer to questions, and if repeatedly queried (for example, 100 times), they'll usually generate the correct answer at least once, but the problem is, they don't know which of their responses is correct. Weak generators produce errors that are easier to detect than strong generators.\n\n### How LLMs Can Amplify Weak Generators\n\nWeaver is a framework for designing a strong verifier by combining multiple weak, imperfect verifiers, leveraging weak supervision to estimate each verifier's accuracy and combining their outputs into a unified score that better reflects true response quality.\n\nThe research demonstrates that Weaver significantly improves over Pass@1—the performance when simply selecting the first candidate response—achieving o3-mini-level accuracy with Llama 3.3 70B Instruct as the generator, and an ensemble of 70B or smaller judge and reward models as the verifiers.\n\nThis approach effectively shows that even weak generators paired with aggregated weak verifiers can achieve strong performance levels, suggesting that verification is indeed a more tractable problem than generation itself.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"29e9d40f-6bba-4dd5-b3d1-08e9cae83847","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:05.999Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"generator-verifier gap verification easier than generation LLM amplify weak generator","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01HbpH22KxiX49mu2WqSfNqW","content":[{"title":"Weaver: Closing the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers · Hazy Research","url":"https://hazyresearch.stanford.edu/blog/2025-06-18-weaver"},{"title":"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1"},{"title":"Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf/2746494c2d2444d3341c92778e3a660a0f237fd2.pdf"},{"title":"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers - Video | MLOps Community","url":"https://home.mlops.community/public/videos/shrinking-the-generation-verification-gap-with-weak-verifiers"},{"title":"Aggregating LLM-Based Weak Verifiers for Spatial Layout Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.05268"},{"title":"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers","url":"https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/pubs/weaver.pdf"},{"title":"Variation in Verification: Understanding Verification Dynamics in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.17995"},{"title":"Shrinking the Generation-Verification Gap with Weak Verifiers","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.18203"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about the generator-verifier gap and how verification relates to generation in LLMs:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nBy aggregating weak, unlabeled verifier signals using weak supervision, Weaver closes the generation-verification gap without fine-tuning, significant human labeling, or architectural changes.\n\n### Verification Can Be Easier Than Generation\n\nLanguage models often already \"know\" the correct answer to questions, and if repeatedly queried (for example, 100 times), they'll usually generate the correct answer at least once, but the problem is, they don't know which of their responses is correct. Weak generators produce errors that are easier to detect than strong generators.\n\n### How LLMs Can Amplify Weak Generators\n\nWeaver is a framework for designing a strong verifier by combining multiple weak, imperfect verifiers, leveraging weak supervision to estimate each verifier's accuracy and combining their outputs into a unified score that better reflects true response quality.\n\nThe research demonstrates that Weaver significantly improves over Pass@1—the performance when simply selecting the first candidate response—achieving o3-mini-level accuracy with Llama 3.3 70B Instruct as the generator, and an ensemble of 70B or smaller judge and reward models as the verifiers.\n\nThis approach effectively shows that even weak generators paired with aggregated weak verifiers can achieve strong performance levels, suggesting that verification is indeed a more tractable problem than generation itself."],"durationSeconds":9.850902374999597,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5ba70cfd-353c-464f-ad2c-0b15b18f9011","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"c046ccac-a183-413b-81fe-b885c98259fd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014MTmp2tim1vSw9Z4dLxx6f","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve DeepMind 2025 evolutionary code search tests fitness\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind AlphaEvolve in Production: AI Agent Recovering 0.7% of Google's Global Compute | Tech Bytes\",\"url\":\"https://techbytes.app/posts/deepmind-alphaevolve-production-deployment/\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond Human Code: How Evolutionary Algorithms like AlphaEvolve Will Shape Next-Gen Apps\",\"url\":\"https://labs.adaline.ai/p/beyond-human-code-how-evolutionary\"},{\"title\":\"Mining Generalizable Activation Functions\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.05688\"},{\"title\":\"How DeepMind’s AlphaEvolve Coding Agent Automates Innovation\",\"url\":\"https://www.techopedia.com/deepmind-alphaevolve-ai-code-evolution\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaEvolve\"},{\"title\":\"CodeEvolve: an open-source evolutionary framework for algorithmic discovery and optimization\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.14150v4\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - google-deepmind/alphaevolve_results · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/google-deepmind/alphaevolve_results\"},{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent for designing advanced algorithms based on large language models such as Gemini, developed by Google DeepMind and unveiled in May 2025.\n\n## How It Works\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary search system that uses Gemini models as mutation and generation operators within a structured program synthesis loop. It leverages an ensemble of state-of-the-art large language models: Gemini Flash maximizes the breadth of ideas explored, while Gemini Pro provides critical depth with insightful suggestions, and together these models propose computer programs that implement algorithmic solutions as code.\n\n## Testing and Fitness Functions\n\nEvery candidate algorithm or code change AlphaEvolve generates is automatically evaluated against a quantitative fitness function. AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics, which provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\n\n## Real-World Results\n\nGoogle DeepMind has confirmed that AlphaEvolve has been continuously running inside Google's production infrastructure since early 2025, recovers 0.7% of Google's worldwide computing resources, accelerated a critical Gemini training kernel by 23%, and is now being deployed at U.S. Department of Energy National Laboratories.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"cb4fa1c8-a646-44b5-b75a-e6d2b50ef079","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:07.484Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve DeepMind 2025 evolutionary code search tests fitness","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01TpTCHmbCmMSmJdZVZQhknu","content":[{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf"},{"title":"DeepMind AlphaEvolve in Production: AI Agent Recovering 0.7% of Google's Global Compute | Tech Bytes","url":"https://techbytes.app/posts/deepmind-alphaevolve-production-deployment/"},{"title":"Beyond Human Code: How Evolutionary Algorithms like AlphaEvolve Will Shape Next-Gen Apps","url":"https://labs.adaline.ai/p/beyond-human-code-how-evolutionary"},{"title":"Mining Generalizable Activation Functions","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.05688"},{"title":"How DeepMind’s AlphaEvolve Coding Agent Automates Innovation","url":"https://www.techopedia.com/deepmind-alphaevolve-ai-code-evolution"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AlphaEvolve"},{"title":"CodeEvolve: an open-source evolutionary framework for algorithmic discovery and optimization","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.14150v4"},{"title":"GitHub - google-deepmind/alphaevolve_results · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/google-deepmind/alphaevolve_results"},{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve:\n\n## Overview\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary coding agent for designing advanced algorithms based on large language models such as Gemini, developed by Google DeepMind and unveiled in May 2025.\n\n## How It Works\n\nAlphaEvolve is an evolutionary search system that uses Gemini models as mutation and generation operators within a structured program synthesis loop. It leverages an ensemble of state-of-the-art large language models: Gemini Flash maximizes the breadth of ideas explored, while Gemini Pro provides critical depth with insightful suggestions, and together these models propose computer programs that implement algorithmic solutions as code.\n\n## Testing and Fitness Functions\n\nEvery candidate algorithm or code change AlphaEvolve generates is automatically evaluated against a quantitative fitness function. AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics, which provide an objective, quantifiable assessment of each solution's accuracy and quality.\n\n## Real-World Results\n\nGoogle DeepMind has confirmed that AlphaEvolve has been continuously running inside Google's production infrastructure since early 2025, recovers 0.7% of Google's worldwide computing resources, accelerated a critical Gemini training kernel by 23%, and is now being deployed at U.S. Department of Energy National Laboratories."],"durationSeconds":11.405641041999683,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c046ccac-a183-413b-81fe-b885c98259fd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
