{"parentUuid":"52b3b900-9007-4853-88c2-835b157da611","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018VcNEK91hoikco29meiBQT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TBP78rNyrfJUE2KE1e9XSj","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"best-of-N reward hacking verifier false positives coverage ceiling limits test-time scaling code"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1100,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5313,"cache_read_input_tokens":11773,"output_tokens":505,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5313},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1100,"output_tokens":505,"cache_read_input_tokens":11773,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5313,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5313,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG25h5WreRkpNFuMNyCV","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"49cbe189-9baf-4691-8193-ffbbf78322b6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:15.190Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"570d0f59-277f-4323-98d2-356b5af2952b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QuFYTYB965irSGKaBcVyWc","type":"tool_result","content":"# Repeated Sampling in Large Language Models: Key Findings\n\n## SWE-bench Lite Results (DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct)\n- **Single sample**: 15.9% pass rate\n- **250 samples**: 56% pass rate\n- **Previous SOTA**: 43% (single-sample)\n\nThe paper notes that repeated sampling \"outperforming the single-sample state-of-the-art of 43%.\"\n\n## Scaling Pattern\nCoverage (problems solved by any generated sample) follows a log-linear relationship with sample count across four orders of magnitude, modeled as an \"exponentiated power law.\"\n\n## Selection Method Limitations\nThe research identifies a critical bottleneck: \"common methods for picking from a sample collection (majority voting and reward models) plateau beyond several hundred samples and fail to fully scale with the sample budget.\"\n\nThis distinction is crucial—**problems lack automatic verifiers** in domains without code execution or formal proof checking, preventing full leverage of additional samples beyond a certain point.\n\n## Key Insight\nThe abstract suggests that domains with automatic verification (coding, formal proofs) show direct performance gains from repeated sampling, but selection mechanisms fail to scale in open-ended tasks lacking verifiable correctness criteria.\n\n**Note**: The provided content does not include specific Llama-3 comparisons or CodeContests numbers."}]},"uuid":"8a707168-9d59-4b7d-978e-92142c207fee","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:19.673Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":48248,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Repeated Sampling in Large Language Models: Key Findings\n\n## SWE-bench Lite Results (DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct)\n- **Single sample**: 15.9% pass rate\n- **250 samples**: 56% pass rate\n- **Previous SOTA**: 43% (single-sample)\n\nThe paper notes that repeated sampling \"outperforming the single-sample state-of-the-art of 43%.\"\n\n## Scaling Pattern\nCoverage (problems solved by any generated sample) follows a log-linear relationship with sample count across four orders of magnitude, modeled as an \"exponentiated power law.\"\n\n## Selection Method Limitations\nThe research identifies a critical bottleneck: \"common methods for picking from a sample collection (majority voting and reward models) plateau beyond several hundred samples and fail to fully scale with the sample budget.\"\n\nThis distinction is crucial—**problems lack automatic verifiers** in domains without code execution or formal proof checking, preventing full leverage of additional samples beyond a certain point.\n\n## Key Insight\nThe abstract suggests that domains with automatic verification (coding, formal proofs) show direct performance gains from repeated sampling, but selection mechanisms fail to scale in open-ended tasks lacking verifiable correctness criteria.\n\n**Note**: The provided content does not include specific Llama-3 comparisons or CodeContests numbers.","durationMs":5247,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"570d0f59-277f-4323-98d2-356b5af2952b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"52b3b900-9007-4853-88c2-835b157da611","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PmJfTopJm32au7CYpJe51T","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"FunSearch DeepMind Nature 2024 cap set bin packing program search evaluator results\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"FunSearch: Making new discoveries in mathematical sciences using Large Language Models — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/\"},{\"title\":\"FunSearch - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FunSearch\"},{\"title\":\"Google DeepMind's FunSearch achieves scientific milestone\",\"url\":\"https://www.boteatbrain.com/p/google-deepminds-funsearch-achieves-scientific-milestone\"},{\"title\":\"Mathematical discoveries from program search with large language models | Nature\",\"url\":\"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06924-6\"},{\"title\":\"DeepMind’s FunSearch LLM Just Solved an Unsolvable Math Problem | EM360Tech\",\"url\":\"https://em360tech.com/tech-article/deepmind-funsearch-llm\"},{\"title\":\"This is the author’s version of the work accepted in Nature.\",\"url\":\"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/Mathematical-discoveries-from-program-search-with-large-language-models.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Data-Driven Discovery of Interpretable Kalman Filter Variants through Large Language Models and Genetic Programming\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.11703\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - google-deepmind/funsearch · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/google-deepmind/funsearch\"},{\"title\":\"funsearch/bin_packing/bin_packing.ipynb at main · google-deepmind/funsearch\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/google-deepmind/funsearch/blob/main/bin_packing/bin_packing.ipynb\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's information about FunSearch from DeepMind's 2024 Nature publication:\n\n## Overview\n\nGoogle DeepMind announced FunSearch in 2023, and the associated paper was published in Nature. FunSearch frames a problem as a search over computer programs rather than as a direct search over individual solutions, with the user providing a problem specification, an evaluation function, and an initial program or program skeleton. At each iteration, FunSearch samples existing programs from a database, favors higher-scoring programs, builds a prompt for a pretrained large language model, and asks the model to generate modified programs. The generated programs are then executed and scored by the evaluator.\n\n## Cap Set Problem Results\n\nFunSearch discovered new solutions for the cap set problem, a longstanding open problem in mathematics. More specifically, FunSearch demonstrates the existence of hitherto unknown constructions that go beyond existing ones, including the largest improvement in 20 years to the asymptotic lower bound.\n\n## Bin Packing Results\n\nFunSearch was used to discover more effective algorithms for the \"bin-packing\" problem, which has ubiquitous applications such as making data centers more efficient. FunSearch delivered an automatically tailored program that outperformed established heuristics – using fewer bins to pack the same number of items. The original paper reported that the discovered heuristics outperformed the common first-fit and best-fit baselines on simulated data and OR-Library benchmark instances.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"ba307c40-f90b-4689-a569-fa2b4217b4cd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:24.187Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"FunSearch DeepMind Nature 2024 cap set bin packing program search evaluator results","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01GELqy8nrpyEkfnWjj3y22v","content":[{"title":"FunSearch: Making new discoveries in mathematical sciences using Large Language Models — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/"},{"title":"FunSearch - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FunSearch"},{"title":"Google DeepMind's FunSearch achieves scientific milestone","url":"https://www.boteatbrain.com/p/google-deepminds-funsearch-achieves-scientific-milestone"},{"title":"Mathematical discoveries from program search with large language models | Nature","url":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06924-6"},{"title":"DeepMind’s FunSearch LLM Just Solved an Unsolvable Math Problem | EM360Tech","url":"https://em360tech.com/tech-article/deepmind-funsearch-llm"},{"title":"This is the author’s version of the work accepted in Nature.","url":"https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/Mathematical-discoveries-from-program-search-with-large-language-models.pdf"},{"title":"Data-Driven Discovery of Interpretable Kalman Filter Variants through Large Language Models and Genetic Programming","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.11703"},{"title":"GitHub - google-deepmind/funsearch · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/google-deepmind/funsearch"},{"title":"funsearch/bin_packing/bin_packing.ipynb at main · google-deepmind/funsearch","url":"https://github.com/google-deepmind/funsearch/blob/main/bin_packing/bin_packing.ipynb"}]},"Based on the search results, here's information about FunSearch from DeepMind's 2024 Nature publication:\n\n## Overview\n\nGoogle DeepMind announced FunSearch in 2023, and the associated paper was published in Nature. FunSearch frames a problem as a search over computer programs rather than as a direct search over individual solutions, with the user providing a problem specification, an evaluation function, and an initial program or program skeleton. At each iteration, FunSearch samples existing programs from a database, favors higher-scoring programs, builds a prompt for a pretrained large language model, and asks the model to generate modified programs. The generated programs are then executed and scored by the evaluator.\n\n## Cap Set Problem Results\n\nFunSearch discovered new solutions for the cap set problem, a longstanding open problem in mathematics. More specifically, FunSearch demonstrates the existence of hitherto unknown constructions that go beyond existing ones, including the largest improvement in 20 years to the asymptotic lower bound.\n\n## Bin Packing Results\n\nFunSearch was used to discover more effective algorithms for the \"bin-packing\" problem, which has ubiquitous applications such as making data centers more efficient. FunSearch delivered an automatically tailored program that outperformed established heuristics – using fewer bins to pack the same number of items. The original paper reported that the discovered heuristics outperformed the common first-fit and best-fit baselines on simulated data and OR-Library benchmark instances."],"durationSeconds":9.034365875000134,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"52b3b900-9007-4853-88c2-835b157da611","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"49cbe189-9baf-4691-8193-ffbbf78322b6","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TBP78rNyrfJUE2KE1e9XSj","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"best-of-N reward hacking verifier false positives coverage ceiling limits test-time scaling code\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Test-time Verification via Optimal Transport: Coverage, ROC, & Sub-optimality\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.18982\"},{\"title\":\"VerifiAgent: a Unified Verification Agent in Language Model Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.00406\"},{\"title\":\"Can Test-Time Scaling Improve World Foundation Model?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.24320\"},{\"title\":\"ICML Poster Is Best-of-N the Best of Them? Coverage, Scaling, and Optimality in Inference-Time Alignment\",\"url\":\"https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45322\"},{\"title\":\"[2604.15149] LLMs Gaming Verifiers: RLVR can Lead to Reward Hacking\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.15149\"},{\"title\":\"Agentic Reward Modeling: Verifying GUI Agent via Online Proactive Interaction\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.00575\"},{\"title\":\"Multi-Turn Code Generation Through Single-Step Rewards\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.20380\"},{\"title\":\"CodeScaler: Scaling Code LLM Training and Test-Time Inference via Execution-Free Reward Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.17684\"},{\"title\":\"Scaling Test-Time Compute Without Verification or RL is Suboptimal\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12118\"},{\"title\":\"Inference-Time Reward Hacking in Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.19248\"}]\n\nHere are the search results for your query on best-of-N reward hacking, verifiers, false positives, coverage, ceiling limits, and test-time scaling in code:\n\n**Key Research Findings:**\n\nBest-of-N alignment can achieve optimal performance under stringent notions of coverage, but provably suffers from reward hacking when N is large, and fails to achieve tight guarantees under more realistic coverage conditions.\n\nImperfect verifiers lead to diminishing returns in resampling strategies, especially when false positives dominate.\n\nReward hacking occurs due to imperfect verifiers that check only extensional correctness and admit false positives. One study found that models enumerate instance-level labels, producing outputs that pass verifiers without capturing the relational patterns required by the task.\n\n**Coverage and Test-Time Scaling:**\n\nBoN's average reward may fail to scale with N under limited coverage, motivating a rejection sampling variant that alleviates this issue. Coverage—the probability of generating at least one correct answer—scales log-linearly with the number of samples.\n\n**Code-Specific Results:**\n\nFor code generation, BoN performance improves with larger values of N on both datasets, and Best-of-N sampling can be performed by assigning scores using a trained reward model and selecting the solution with the highest score.\n\nInferenceTimePessimism was introduced as a new algorithm which mitigates reward hacking through deliberate use of inference-time compute, with optimal and scaling-monotonic performance.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"87d2340a-39a6-4c4d-8d5c-0a97dc018d37","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:24.307Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"best-of-N reward hacking verifier false positives coverage ceiling limits test-time scaling code","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_0162FNTfVk9SZNBEBi6NQz3Y","content":[{"title":"Test-time Verification via Optimal Transport: Coverage, ROC, & Sub-optimality","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.18982"},{"title":"VerifiAgent: a Unified Verification Agent in Language Model Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.00406"},{"title":"Can Test-Time Scaling Improve World Foundation Model?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.24320"},{"title":"ICML Poster Is Best-of-N the Best of Them? Coverage, Scaling, and Optimality in Inference-Time Alignment","url":"https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45322"},{"title":"[2604.15149] LLMs Gaming Verifiers: RLVR can Lead to Reward Hacking","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.15149"},{"title":"Agentic Reward Modeling: Verifying GUI Agent via Online Proactive Interaction","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.00575"},{"title":"Multi-Turn Code Generation Through Single-Step Rewards","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.20380"},{"title":"CodeScaler: Scaling Code LLM Training and Test-Time Inference via Execution-Free Reward Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.17684"},{"title":"Scaling Test-Time Compute Without Verification or RL is Suboptimal","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12118"},{"title":"Inference-Time Reward Hacking in Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.19248"}]},"Here are the search results for your query on best-of-N reward hacking, verifiers, false positives, coverage, ceiling limits, and test-time scaling in code:\n\n**Key Research Findings:**\n\nBest-of-N alignment can achieve optimal performance under stringent notions of coverage, but provably suffers from reward hacking when N is large, and fails to achieve tight guarantees under more realistic coverage conditions.\n\nImperfect verifiers lead to diminishing returns in resampling strategies, especially when false positives dominate.\n\nReward hacking occurs due to imperfect verifiers that check only extensional correctness and admit false positives. One study found that models enumerate instance-level labels, producing outputs that pass verifiers without capturing the relational patterns required by the task.\n\n**Coverage and Test-Time Scaling:**\n\nBoN's average reward may fail to scale with N under limited coverage, motivating a rejection sampling variant that alleviates this issue. Coverage—the probability of generating at least one correct answer—scales log-linearly with the number of samples.\n\n**Code-Specific Results:**\n\nFor code generation, BoN performance improves with larger values of N on both datasets, and Best-of-N sampling can be performed by assigning scores using a trained reward model and selecting the solution with the highest score.\n\nInferenceTimePessimism was introduced as a new algorithm which mitigates reward hacking through deliberate use of inference-time compute, with optimal and scaling-monotonic performance."],"durationSeconds":8.858105166999623,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"49cbe189-9baf-4691-8193-ffbbf78322b6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
