{"parentUuid":"7526d0fc-d644-46a8-9a89-e5767b0c3e85","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01AVqE7KtcAmmyeZZFePFxgB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TRZE4kttRaTAUhDckCJKZ5","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1","prompt":"Extract exact numbers: how much does Weaver improve over Pass@1? What is the generation-verification gap defined as? What accuracy does Llama 3.3 70B + weak verifiers reach (claim of o3-mini level)? Any per-benchmark numbers (MATH, GPQA, MMLU). How many samples used. Any quantification that verification is easier than generation."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4536,"cache_read_input_tokens":17086,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4536,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG26vzhKFSRGfxvmbE3U","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"5124a85f-e37f-42db-8fff-fdecf1018e9e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:30.886Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"5124a85f-e37f-42db-8fff-fdecf1018e9e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01AVqE7KtcAmmyeZZFePFxgB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QJ1FBVPdihv84q8J3nKLeC","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"AlphaEvolve 4x4 complex matrix multiplication 48 multiplications Strassen improvement"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4536,"cache_read_input_tokens":17086,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4536,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG26vzhKFSRGfxvmbE3U","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"25b99919-3c1a-433f-b144-17a1d36e99d4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:31.098Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"5124a85f-e37f-42db-8fff-fdecf1018e9e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TRZE4kttRaTAUhDckCJKZ5","type":"tool_result","content":"# Weaver Framework: Key Quantitative Findings\n\n## Improvement Over Pass@1\nWeaver achieves **17.9% improvement for 8B models and 14.5% for 70B models** across reasoning and mathematics tasks compared to Pass@1 (first response selection).\n\n## Generation-Verification Gap Definition\nThe gap is defined as: **\"Pass@K - Success Rate.\"** A large positive gap indicates correct answers exist but the verification strategy fails to identify them consistently.\n\n## Frontier Model Performance Claims\nWeaver with Llama 3.3 70B reaches **87.7% average accuracy**, coming within **0.5% of o3-mini's 86.7%** performance, despite using a non-reasoning generator with repeated sampling rather than specialized post-training.\n\n## Per-Benchmark Results (K=100 generations)\n| Dataset | Weaver | Pass@100 (Oracle) |\n|---------|--------|------------------|\n| MATH500 | 93.4% | 98.6% |\n| GPQA Diamond | 72.1% | 81.0% |\n| MMLU College | 94.9% | 96.0% |\n| MMLU Pro | 90.2% | 92.0% |\n\n## Sample Count\nEvaluations use **K=100 repeated samples** per query for main results, with scaling experiments testing K=2⁰ to K=2¹⁰.\n\n## Verification vs. Generation Difficulty\nThe paper notes achieving \"o3-mini-level accuracy with Llama 3.3 70B\" through verification scaling rather than generation model finetuning, suggesting verification offers a more accessible path to frontier performance than developing specialized reasoning models."}]},"uuid":"27b229a7-2621-49b8-a31a-57dfdadbf2ff","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:38.632Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":2580469,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Weaver Framework: Key Quantitative Findings\n\n## Improvement Over Pass@1\nWeaver achieves **17.9% improvement for 8B models and 14.5% for 70B models** across reasoning and mathematics tasks compared to Pass@1 (first response selection).\n\n## Generation-Verification Gap Definition\nThe gap is defined as: **\"Pass@K - Success Rate.\"** A large positive gap indicates correct answers exist but the verification strategy fails to identify them consistently.\n\n## Frontier Model Performance Claims\nWeaver with Llama 3.3 70B reaches **87.7% average accuracy**, coming within **0.5% of o3-mini's 86.7%** performance, despite using a non-reasoning generator with repeated sampling rather than specialized post-training.\n\n## Per-Benchmark Results (K=100 generations)\n| Dataset | Weaver | Pass@100 (Oracle) |\n|---------|--------|------------------|\n| MATH500 | 93.4% | 98.6% |\n| GPQA Diamond | 72.1% | 81.0% |\n| MMLU College | 94.9% | 96.0% |\n| MMLU Pro | 90.2% | 92.0% |\n\n## Sample Count\nEvaluations use **K=100 repeated samples** per query for main results, with scaling experiments testing K=2⁰ to K=2¹⁰.\n\n## Verification vs. Generation Difficulty\nThe paper notes achieving \"o3-mini-level accuracy with Llama 3.3 70B\" through verification scaling rather than generation model finetuning, suggesting verification offers a more accessible path to frontier performance than developing specialized reasoning models.","durationMs":7142,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"5124a85f-e37f-42db-8fff-fdecf1018e9e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"25b99919-3c1a-433f-b144-17a1d36e99d4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QJ1FBVPdihv84q8J3nKLeC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AlphaEvolve 4x4 complex matrix multiplication 48 multiplications Strassen improvement\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind\",\"url\":\"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\"},{\"title\":\"Meet AlphaEvolve, the Google AI that writes its own code—and just saved millions in computing costs | VentureBeat\",\"url\":\"https://venturebeat.com/ai/meet-alphaevolve-the-google-ai-that-writes-its-own-code-and-just-saved-millions-in-computing-costs\"},{\"title\":\"The Matrix Multiplication Revolution: How AlphaEvolve Shattered a 56-Year Mathematical Record | by Pratik Deshmukh | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@deshmukhpratik931/the-matrix-multiplication-revolution-how-alphaevolve-shattered-a-56-year-mathematical-record-c9e61b70bae2\"},{\"title\":\"Paper Review: AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery | by Andrew Lukyanenko | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - PhialsBasement/AlphaEvolve-MatrixMul-Verification: Verification of Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve 48-multiplication matrix algorithm, a breakthrough in matrix multiplication after 56 years. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/PhialsBasement/AlphaEvolve-MatrixMul-Verification\"},{\"title\":\"Google's AlphaEvolve Solved What Stumped Mathematicians for 56 Years (Here's Why You Should Care)\",\"url\":\"https://sidecar.ai/blog/googles-alphaevolve-solved-what-stumped-mathematicians-for-56-years-heres-why-you-should-care\"},{\"title\":\"robinhouston: \\\"The new AlphaEvolve paper from…\\\" - Mathstodon\",\"url\":\"https://mathstodon.xyz/@robinhouston/114507937280899656\"},{\"title\":\"VLSI Implementation of Alphaevolve Based Rank-48 Algorithm for 4×4 Real-Valued Matrix Multiplication | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/403375592_VLSI_Implementation_of_Alphaevolve_Based_Rank-48_Algorithm_for_44_Real-Valued_Matrix_Multiplication\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve and 4x4 complex matrix multiplication:\n\nAlphaEvolve's procedure found an algorithm to multiply 4x4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications, improving upon Strassen's 1969 algorithm that was previously known as the best in this setting.\n\nMore specifically, the breakthrough allows two 4×4 complex-valued matrices to be multiplied using 48 scalar multiplications instead of 49 — a discovery that had eluded mathematicians since Volker Strassen's landmark work.\n\nThis represents a significant achievement: breaking a 56-year-old barrier and surpassing Strassen's long-standing 49-multiplication approach for characteristic 0 fields. While a single multiplication reduction might seem minor, it represents the first improvement to Strassen's algorithm for 4×4 complex matrices in over five decades and has significant implications for larger matrices when applied recursively.\n\nIt's worth noting that there is some academic discussion about whether 48 multiplications for 4x4 matrices was truly unprecedented in all mathematical contexts, but AlphaEvolve's achievement appears to represent the first such improvement discovered through an automated AI algorithm-design approach.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b5ba6f4f-8f99-4bb2-9cbb-e30b34ab1430","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:39.215Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AlphaEvolve 4x4 complex matrix multiplication 48 multiplications Strassen improvement","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01JjDqRvVw9YeMF87ktPWHoe","content":[{"title":"AlphaEvolve: A Gemini-powered coding agent for designing advanced algorithms — Google DeepMind","url":"https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/"},{"title":"Meet AlphaEvolve, the Google AI that writes its own code—and just saved millions in computing costs | VentureBeat","url":"https://venturebeat.com/ai/meet-alphaevolve-the-google-ai-that-writes-its-own-code-and-just-saved-millions-in-computing-costs"},{"title":"The Matrix Multiplication Revolution: How AlphaEvolve Shattered a 56-Year Mathematical Record | by Pratik Deshmukh | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@deshmukhpratik931/the-matrix-multiplication-revolution-how-alphaevolve-shattered-a-56-year-mathematical-record-c9e61b70bae2"},{"title":"Paper Review: AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery | by Andrew Lukyanenko | Medium","url":"https://artgor.medium.com/paper-review-alphaevolve-a-coding-agent-for-scientific-and-algorithmic-discovery-5732a876c2e2"},{"title":"GitHub - PhialsBasement/AlphaEvolve-MatrixMul-Verification: Verification of Google DeepMind's AlphaEvolve 48-multiplication matrix algorithm, a breakthrough in matrix multiplication after 56 years. · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/PhialsBasement/AlphaEvolve-MatrixMul-Verification"},{"title":"Google's AlphaEvolve Solved What Stumped Mathematicians for 56 Years (Here's Why You Should Care)","url":"https://sidecar.ai/blog/googles-alphaevolve-solved-what-stumped-mathematicians-for-56-years-heres-why-you-should-care"},{"title":"robinhouston: \"The new AlphaEvolve paper from…\" - Mathstodon","url":"https://mathstodon.xyz/@robinhouston/114507937280899656"},{"title":"VLSI Implementation of Alphaevolve Based Rank-48 Algorithm for 4×4 Real-Valued Matrix Multiplication | Request PDF","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/403375592_VLSI_Implementation_of_Alphaevolve_Based_Rank-48_Algorithm_for_44_Real-Valued_Matrix_Multiplication"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about AlphaEvolve and 4x4 complex matrix multiplication:\n\nAlphaEvolve's procedure found an algorithm to multiply 4x4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications, improving upon Strassen's 1969 algorithm that was previously known as the best in this setting.\n\nMore specifically, the breakthrough allows two 4×4 complex-valued matrices to be multiplied using 48 scalar multiplications instead of 49 — a discovery that had eluded mathematicians since Volker Strassen's landmark work.\n\nThis represents a significant achievement: breaking a 56-year-old barrier and surpassing Strassen's long-standing 49-multiplication approach for characteristic 0 fields. While a single multiplication reduction might seem minor, it represents the first improvement to Strassen's algorithm for 4×4 complex matrices in over five decades and has significant implications for larger matrices when applied recursively.\n\nIt's worth noting that there is some academic discussion about whether 48 multiplications for 4x4 matrices was truly unprecedented in all mathematical contexts, but AlphaEvolve's achievement appears to represent the first such improvement discovered through an automated AI algorithm-design approach."],"durationSeconds":7.560213999999687,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"25b99919-3c1a-433f-b144-17a1d36e99d4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
