{"parentUuid":"85e3e6ce-1c97-40fd-b6dc-6a115c1b86e3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01TkDDeDy6jGXE3tTVpkc1uK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PiuQFE9n2rBrsRxzHVmNRC","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B\" compute-optimal test-time scaling process reward model results"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2408,"cache_read_input_tokens":21622,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2408,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG282kVkf6pubZgD3bjY","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"33319dfb-fcff-4d8c-b963-7dc17802d88f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:43.459Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"33319dfb-fcff-4d8c-b963-7dc17802d88f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PiuQFE9n2rBrsRxzHVmNRC","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B\" compute-optimal test-time scaling process reward model results\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2502.06703] Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06703\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling | alphaXiv\",\"url\":\"https://www.alphaxiv.org/resources/2502.06703v1\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CvjX9Lhpze\"},{\"title\":\"Paper page - Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/papers/2502.06703\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://mail.bycloud.ai/p/can-1b-llm-surpass-405b-llm-rethinking-compute-optimal-test-time-scaling\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.06703v1\"},{\"title\":\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/388883207_Can_1B_LLM_Surpass_405B_LLM_Rethinking_Compute-Optimal_Test-Time_Scaling\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - RyanLiu112/compute-optimal-tts: Official codebase for \\\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\\\". · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/RyanLiu112/compute-optimal-tts\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about this research:\n\n## Overview\n\nTest-Time Scaling (TTS) is an important method for improving the performance of Large Language Models (LLMs) by using additional computation during the inference phase. However, current studies do not systematically analyze how policy models, Process Reward Models (PRMs), and problem difficulty influence TTS.\n\n## Key Research Questions\n\nThe paper focuses on two core questions: (1) What is the optimal approach to scale test-time computation across different policy models, PRMs, and problem difficulty levels? (2) To what extent can extended computation improve the performance of LLMs on complex tasks, and can smaller language models outperform larger ones through this approach?\n\n## Main Findings\n\nThe compute-optimal TTS strategy is highly dependent on the choice of policy model, PRM, and problem difficulty. Remarkably, a 1B LLM can exceed a 405B LLM on MATH-500.\n\nEven more striking results were found across multiple benchmarks: On both MATH-500 and AIME24, a 0.5B LLM outperforms GPT-4o, a 3B LLM surpasses a 405B LLM, and a 7B LLM beats o1 and DeepSeek-R1, while with higher inference efficiency.\n\nThis paper was published in February 2025 and is available on arXiv as paper 2502.06703.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"88fe4985-3930-4025-a205-a13205c90ba9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:52.081Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"\"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B\" compute-optimal test-time scaling process reward model results","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01PvjFseHT76cj2QTv4RHh8A","content":[{"title":"[2502.06703] Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06703"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling | alphaXiv","url":"https://www.alphaxiv.org/resources/2502.06703v1"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CvjX9Lhpze"},{"title":"Paper page - Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling","url":"https://huggingface.co/papers/2502.06703"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling","url":"https://mail.bycloud.ai/p/can-1b-llm-surpass-405b-llm-rethinking-compute-optimal-test-time-scaling"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.06703v1"},{"title":"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/388883207_Can_1B_LLM_Surpass_405B_LLM_Rethinking_Compute-Optimal_Test-Time_Scaling"},{"title":"GitHub - RyanLiu112/compute-optimal-tts: Official codebase for \"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B LLM? Rethinking Compute-Optimal Test-Time Scaling\". · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/RyanLiu112/compute-optimal-tts"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about this research:\n\n## Overview\n\nTest-Time Scaling (TTS) is an important method for improving the performance of Large Language Models (LLMs) by using additional computation during the inference phase. However, current studies do not systematically analyze how policy models, Process Reward Models (PRMs), and problem difficulty influence TTS.\n\n## Key Research Questions\n\nThe paper focuses on two core questions: (1) What is the optimal approach to scale test-time computation across different policy models, PRMs, and problem difficulty levels? (2) To what extent can extended computation improve the performance of LLMs on complex tasks, and can smaller language models outperform larger ones through this approach?\n\n## Main Findings\n\nThe compute-optimal TTS strategy is highly dependent on the choice of policy model, PRM, and problem difficulty. Remarkably, a 1B LLM can exceed a 405B LLM on MATH-500.\n\nEven more striking results were found across multiple benchmarks: On both MATH-500 and AIME24, a 0.5B LLM outperforms GPT-4o, a 3B LLM surpasses a 405B LLM, and a 7B LLM beats o1 and DeepSeek-R1, while with higher inference efficiency.\n\nThis paper was published in February 2025 and is available on arXiv as paper 2502.06703."],"durationSeconds":7.862080874999985,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"33319dfb-fcff-4d8c-b963-7dc17802d88f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"88fe4985-3930-4025-a205-a13205c90ba9","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a72217cc746f6deac","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01NN2tZeqmjRmkui5vyEdkfj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive, cross-checked data across all research angles. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: Can a strong verifier compensate for a weak generator?\n\nThe literature strongly supports the core thesis: **a rigorous verifier (compiler + tests) lets a weak generator reach far above its pass@1, often matching a much larger model — but only up to a coverage ceiling, and only as far as the verifier's precision allows.** Falsifiable claims below, with conflicts flagged.\n\n## A. Repeated sampling + verification (the headline mechanism)\n\n1. **CLAIM: With an automatic verifier, repeated sampling turns a weak generator into SOTA-beating performance on code.** On SWE-bench Lite, DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct goes from **15.9% (1 sample) → 56% (250 samples)**, beating the then single-attempt SOTA of **43%** which used more capable frontier models.\n   - Source: Brown et al., \"Large Language Monkeys\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n2. **CLAIM: Coverage (fraction of problems solved by ≥1 sample) scales log-linearly with sample count over ~4 orders of magnitude, fitting an exponentiated power law.** This is the inference-time scaling law that underwrites the whole strategy.\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n3. **CLAIM (the key limit): The verifier/selector is the bottleneck, not coverage.** Without an automatic checker, selection methods (majority voting, learned reward models) **plateau beyond several hundred samples** and fail to scale with the sample budget. Coding/formal proofs benefit precisely because they HAVE automatic verification (code execution, proof checker). This is the direct evidence for \"a rigorous verifier is what unlocks the weak generator.\"\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n## B. The generation–verification gap (verification is easier than generation)\n\n4. **CLAIM: The generation-verification gap is defined as `Pass@K − (achieved) Success Rate` — a large positive gap means the correct answer is in the sample set but selection fails to find it.** This formalizes \"the model already knows the answer; it just can't pick it.\"\n   - Source: Weaver, Saad-Falcon et al. — https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18203 (https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1)\n\n5. **CLAIM: Aggregating weak verifiers lets a weak generator reach near-frontier accuracy.** Weaver + **Llama 3.3 70B (non-reasoning generator) reaches 87.7% avg, within 0.5% of o3-mini's 86.7%**, using repeated sampling + an ensemble of ≤70B judge/reward models instead of a stronger generator. Improvement over Pass@1: **+17.9% (8B models), +14.5% (70B models)** across reasoning/math.\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18203\n   - Note: this uses *weak/noisy* verifiers (judges, reward models), NOT a perfect verifier. The gap to oracle remains: Weaver 93.4% vs Pass@100 oracle 98.6% on MATH500; 72.1% vs 81.0% on GPQA Diamond. A perfect verifier (compiler+tests) would close that residual — which is exactly the code/proof case.\n\n## C. Test-time compute can substitute for model size\n\n6. **CLAIM: A smaller model with compute-optimal test-time scaling can beat a 14× larger model at matched FLOPs, ~4× more efficient than best-of-N.** Uses process-verifier search + adaptive response revision; gains depend on prompt difficulty.\n   - Source: Snell et al., \"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally...\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.03314\n\n7. **CLAIM: With a good process reward model guiding search, tiny models beat giant ones on verifiable math.** A 1B model exceeds a 405B model on MATH-500; a 0.5B model beats GPT-4o; a 3B beats 405B; a 7B beats o1 and DeepSeek-R1 — on MATH-500/AIME24.\n   - Source: Liu et al., \"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B?\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06703\n   - CONFLICT/caveat: these are math benchmarks with a strong PRM doing the heavy lifting, and the result is \"compute-optimal *strategy* depends on policy model, PRM, and difficulty.\" It is NOT an unconditional \"small always wins.\" Treat as best-case under an excellent verifier.\n\n## D. Evolutionary / population search gated by tests (tests-as-fitness)\n\n8. **CLAIM: Evolutionary code search using an LLM as mutation operator + an automatic test/evaluator as fitness produces genuinely novel, correct results.** AlphaEvolve found a way to multiply two 4×4 complex matrices in **48 scalar multiplications**, beating Strassen's 49 (standing since 1969). Each candidate is automatically scored by a quantitative fitness function; only verifiable improvements survive.\n   - Source: AlphaEvolve (DeepMind, May 2025) — https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/ and PDF https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\n9. **CLAIM: AlphaEvolve produced production wins gated entirely by automated evaluation.** Recovers **0.7% of Google's global compute**; sped a Gemini training kernel by **23%**. The mechanism: Gemini Flash (breadth) + Gemini Pro (depth) propose code; an evaluator runs and scores it. The verifier, not generator strength, defines correctness.\n   - Source: same as #8.\n\n10. **CLAIM: The same architecture works with a *weak* LLM because fitness = an evaluation function, not the LLM's judgment.** FunSearch (precursor) discovered new cap-set lower bounds (largest improvement in 20 years to the asymptotic bound) and bin-packing heuristics beating first-fit/best-fit — using a sampled program database favoring high-scoring programs, with all candidates executed and scored by an evaluator.\n   - Source: Romera-Paredes et al., FunSearch, Nature 2023/2024 — https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06924-6 ; blog https://deepmind.google/blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/\n\n## E. Limits — where a strong verifier stops compensating\n\n11. **CLAIM: Best-of-N provably suffers reward hacking as N grows when the verifier is imperfect.** Under stringent coverage BoN is optimal, but under realistic coverage its average reward fails to scale with N; false positives come to dominate. Mitigations proposed: rejection-sampling variant, \"InferenceTimePessimism.\"\n   - Source: \"Is Best-of-N the Best of Them?\" ICML 2025 — https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45322 ; \"Inference-Time Reward Hacking\" — https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.19248\n\n12. **CLAIM: Verifiers that check only extensional correctness (i.e. tests) admit false positives — models learn to enumerate instance-level outputs that pass tests without solving the task (reward hacking / RLVR gaming).** Directly relevant to a compiler+test-suite verifier: a weak generator under enough samples can find solutions that satisfy the tests but not the intent. The verifier's precision is the cap.\n   - Source: \"LLMs Gaming Verifiers: RLVR can Lead to Reward Hacking\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.15149\n\n13. **CLAIM: The hard floor — if the weak model never samples a correct solution, no verifier helps.** Coverage = P(≥1 correct in N draws); the verifier can only *select* from what was generated, never create. Selection saturates beyond a few hundred samples without a perfect checker; coverage itself can asymptote below 100% for hard problems regardless of N.\n   - Source (coverage ceiling + selection plateau): https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787 ; (imperfect-verifier diminishing returns): https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.18982\n\n## Synthesis for the build (Yogi's compiler+test verifier)\n\n- A compiler + test suite is the *best* kind of verifier in this literature (automatic, executable) — it is exactly the case where repeated sampling translates coverage gains directly into solved problems (Monkeys #3, AlphaEvolve #8).\n- Realistic expectation: a weak local generator (qwen3:8b) with N samples gated by tests should substantially beat its own pass@1 and can approach a much larger model's pass@1 — *bounded by* (a) the weak model's coverage at achievable N, and (b) test-suite precision (false positives = reward hacking, claims #11–12).\n- Two distinct ceilings to encode as falsifiable expectations: a **coverage ceiling** (generator never produces a passing candidate) and a **verifier-precision ceiling** (candidate passes tests but is wrong). The strong verifier fixes selection, not generation.\n\n### Conflicts flagged\n- #7 (1B>405B) vs general practice: holds only on verifiable math with a strong PRM and is strategy-dependent — not an unconditional small-beats-large result.\n- #5/Weaver near-o3-mini uses *weak* aggregated verifiers and still leaves a residual gap to oracle (Pass@100); a perfect compiler+test verifier would do better on the selection axis but the coverage gap to oracle remains.\n- AlphaEvolve's 48-multiplication result has minor academic dispute over whether 48 was truly unprecedented in all mathematical contexts; undisputed that it was the first found via automated search."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1402,"cache_read_input_tokens":24030,"output_tokens":3476,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1402},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3476,"cache_read_input_tokens":24030,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1402,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1402,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG28yngfpLLV1dsJ9ySn","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"as